"# Appendix H — Common Desktop Tasks Under a Logic Lens

Where we take five ordinary things a computer does every day and look
at each through the logic developed in this book. The point: logic is
not a niche subject; it is what your computer is *always* doing, and
knowing the vocabulary lets you see it.

Five tasks. Not exhaustive. Each is a specific example of a logic in
action.

## Task 1: File search

You type a query into the search bar. The system returns matching files.

*Logic view.* File search is *first-order query answering* over a
relational database. Each file is an *object*; each property (name,
extension, size, modification date, path) is a *predicate*; the query
is a *conjunction of atomic constraints*.

Query: *find text files modified in the last week larger than 10 KB.*

    ∃ f. (text-file? f) ∧ (modified-since f last-week) ∧ (size-gt f 10K)

The search engine constructs a plan — which index to use, which
predicate to evaluate first — that minimizes work. This is *query
optimization*, and it is essentially proof-search: build the answer by
combining rules and facts efficiently.

Modern search tools (Spotlight, Windows Search, Bloomsearch, ripgrep
with tag files) all use this pattern. The user speaks propositional
constraints; the system compiles them into a first-order query;
indices support fast retrieval.

## Task 2: Spell checking

Every word you type is checked against a dictionary. Misspelled words
are underlined.

*Logic view.* Spell checking is a *decision procedure* — the theory in
question is *word membership in a dictionary*. The decision procedure
is:

    is-word(w) ≡ ∃ entry ∈ dictionary. entry = w

Plain lookup. But modern spell checkers also do *approximate matching*
— *fuzzy* logic:

    approximately-a-word(w) ≡ ∃ entry. edit-distance(w, entry) ≤ 2

This is fuzzy retrieval (chapter 14). The edit distance is a graded
similarity; matches within a threshold produce suggestions.

Autocorrect goes further: it picks the *most likely intended word*
given context. This is Bayesian: `P(intended | typed)` computed via
Bayes' theorem, with `P(typed | intended)` estimated from a
misspelling model and `P(intended)` from a language model.

## Task 3: File permissions

You try to open a file. The system checks whether you have permission.

*Logic view.* File permissions are a *modal / deontic* system. The
modality is *permitted-to*. The rules:

    permitted(user, action, file) ≡
      (owner(file, user) ∧ owner-permits(file, action)) ∨
      (group-member(user, group(file)) ∧ group-permits(file, action)) ∨
      other-permits(file, action)

The check is a *SAT problem* in disguise: given the permission bits and
the user's identity, is the *permission formula* satisfied?

More sophisticated systems (Windows ACLs, Linux capabilities, macOS
sandbox) use richer permission logics with role-based access control
(RBAC) or attribute-based access control (ABAC). These are
propositional-to-first-order logics of authorization — a large research
literature exists (Sandhu-Coyne-Feinstein-Youman 1996; Halpern-Weissman
2003).

Formal verification of permission systems catches subtle bugs. The
seL4 microkernel's authorization system has been mechanically verified
in Isabelle — proving that no user can gain unintended access. That
proof is a very serious piece of formal logic.

## Task 4: Undo

You press Ctrl-Z. The last operation is undone.

*Logic view.* Undo is *inverse execution* in a *linear-logic* frame.
Every operation consumes some resources (the old state) and produces
others (the new state). Undo reverses that.

For undo to work, every operation must be *invertible* — the old state
must be recoverable from the new state and the operation. Some
operations are naturally invertible (character insertion; the inverse
is deletion of the same character at the same position). Others are
not (destructive commands; you cannot un-shred a file).

Systems that support unlimited undo maintain a *log* of operations
plus a *snapshot* of the state at the beginning. Undo replays the log
backward through inverses. This is *event sourcing* — a database
pattern where the source of truth is the sequence of events, and the
current state is a computed view.

Linear-logic types can *statically* verify that a set of operations is
undoable: each operation's inverse must exist and must consume-produce
the reverse of what the operation consumed-produced. Rust's ownership
system enforces something related for memory operations.

## Task 5: Version control

You commit a change. Later, you merge your branch with someone else's.

*Logic view.* Version control is *proof-carrying code* meets *event
sourcing* meets *partial-order semantics*.

Each commit is a *transformation* — a function from the old repository
state to a new one. The commit hash is a cryptographic proof that the
transformation was applied to the specific old state. Modifications
form a *DAG* (directed acyclic graph) whose ordering is a partial
order over commits.

Merging is *concurrent-computation reasoning*: given two branches that
diverged from a common ancestor, compute a merged state that
incorporates both sets of changes. The three-way merge algorithm
computes the merge by considering each divergent hunk and either:

- Taking one side's version (if the other didn't change it), or
- Combining changes (if the changes are compatible), or
- Reporting a *conflict* (if the changes cannot be reconciled).

The formal underpinning is *conflict-free replicated data types*
(CRDTs) and *operational transformation* — bodies of research that
apply category theory and concurrency logic to synchronization
problems. Git specifically uses a simpler line-based algorithm, but
the theoretical work is what informed its design.

Every distributed system with eventual consistency implements some
version of this logic. Google Docs, iCloud, and distributed databases
all use ideas from this territory.

## The pattern

Each of these desktop tasks *is* logic. The logic is often hidden — a
user sees a search bar, not a first-order query engine. But the
mathematics underneath is exactly what this book has developed:
propositional and predicate reasoning, decision procedures, modal and
linear logics, category-theoretic composition.

The value of seeing this: when you build such systems, you can *reach
for* the logic that fits and use its known algorithms. Search engines
built without SAT/SMT are reinventing SAT/SMT badly. Permission
systems built without modal logic are reinventing modal logic badly.
Undo built without linear logic is often *insecure* — because the
inverses were not thought through rigorously.

The logic in this book is not academic. It is what powers your desktop,
your phone, your car's autopilot, and your bank's ledger. Knowing it
lets you build these things well, and — when they fail — lets you
diagnose the failures at the level they actually occur.

## What to try

Pick a small task you do every day (search, edit, undo, save). Model
it in one of the logics of this book. Which predicates? Which rules?
Which axioms? The exercise makes the logic tangible.

Look up how one of these desktop tasks is *actually* implemented in an
open-source system. Look at Emacs' undo, or ripgrep's search, or
Git's merge. Find the underlying logic. Compare to the mathematical
version. The gap between theory and practice is instructive.

Design a new desktop task and specify its correctness in a logic.
*When I press this key, this and this and this should happen; nothing
else should happen.* Encode that specification in the language of
Hoare logic or temporal logic. This is what formal methods engineers
do; it is a slow, exacting practice, and it catches bugs that
would otherwise ship.

## Closing

Logic is everywhere in computing. This appendix has scratched at five
examples; a hundred more exist. Every subsystem you touch has some
logic under the hood. Knowing the logic gives you leverage over the
subsystem: better understanding, better diagnosis, better design.

The Book of Logic ends with this practical reminder: the material is
not abstract. It is what your computer is doing right now, in the
window you are looking at, on the screen you are reading. Every task
that a computer performs is, at bottom, a proof or a computation or a
decision procedure. Logic is not a niche field. It is the field.

Go build.
"
